OVERVIEW

  This file documents the on-disk binary format of the traditional 512-byte
  Master Boot Record as used by MBR88.  It covers the standard MBR fields
  common to all MBR-partitioned disks, plus the MBR88-specific extensions.

  Fields marked [MBR88] are only present in MBR88 images and are not part
  of the traditional MBR specification.

  The MBR partition table format is compatible with operating systems from
  MS-DOS 2.0 (1983) through current Linux kernels, and with everything
  in between that matters: FreeDOS, DR-DOS, OS/2, Windows through at least
  Windows 10, and ELKS.  MBR88 boot records have been tested on FreeDOS
  and ELKS; the partition table itself is read correctly by anything that
  speaks traditional MBR.

  The MBR format was introduced with IBM PC DOS 2.0 in 1983, designed for
  the original IBM PC XT.  In those 512 bytes live the boot code, the
  partition table, a handful of compatibility fields added over the years,
  and -- in the MBR88 boot record -- a boot menu and labels for up to four
  partitions.  Not bad for a sector that most tools treat as sacred and
  untouchable.

================================================================================
MEMORY MAP
================================================================================

  Offset  Size   Description
  ------  ----   -----------
  0x000   3      Jump instruction to boot code entry point
  0x003   438    Boot code  [see note 1]
  0x1B0   1      [MBR88] Code slack byte (reserved, always 0x00)
  0x1B1   1      [MBR88] Cassini byte (always 0xD9)  [see note 2]
  0x1B2   5      [MBR88] Signature: ASCII 'mbr88'
  0x1B7   1      [MBR88] Version byte (high nibble=major, low nibble=minor)
  0x1B8   4      Disk ID (32-bit little-endian; 0x00000000 = not set)
  0x1BC   2      Write-protect flag (0x5A5A = read-only hint; 0x0000 = normal)
  0x1BE   64     Partition table (4 x 16-byte entries)
  0x1FE   2      Boot signature: 0x55 0xAA

  Total: 512 bytes.

  Note 1: In a generic DOS MBR, the boot code region extends from 0x003 to
  0x1BD (443 bytes less any data the code itself stores in that region).
  MBR88 uses 0x041-0x080 of that range for boot menu label slots, and the
  bytes immediately before 0x1B2 for its signature preamble.

  Note 2: [MBR88] 0xD9 at offset 0x1B1 is the Cassini byte -- the last byte
  of telemetry received from the Cassini spacecraft as it entered Saturn's
  atmosphere on September 15, 2017.  After 0xD9, there was no more data.
  It is preserved here in memory of the mission.

================================================================================
MBRHDR REGION (0x000-0x002)
================================================================================

  Offset  Size   Description
  ------  ----   -----------
  0x000   3      Jump: typically EB xx 90 (short JMP + NOP) or E9 xx xx
                 (near JMP) to the actual boot code entry point past the
                 data area.

================================================================================
BOOT CODE REGION (0x003-0x1AF)  [MBR88 layout]
================================================================================

  In a standard DOS MBR this entire range is executable code.  MBR88 uses
  the low end of this region for boot menu label storage and places its
  code above that.

  [MBR88] Boot menu label slots occupy 0x041-0x080 (four 16-byte slots).
  See BOOT MENU LABEL SLOTS below for the slot format.

  The remaining bytes are MBR88 boot code.  The final byte of boot code
  sits at 0x1AF.

================================================================================
BOOT MENU LABEL SLOTS (0x041-0x080)  [MBR88 only]
================================================================================

  MBR88 stores a display label for each of the four partition table entries
  in four consecutive 16-byte slots beginning at offset 0x041.

  Slot layout (16 bytes each):

    Bytes 0-10   Label text: 1 to 11 printable ASCII characters.
    Byte  N      Terminator: CR (0x0D), LF (0x0A), or NUL (0x00).
                 N is the index of the first terminator byte, so a label
                 shorter than 11 characters terminates before byte 10.
    Bytes N+1-15 Zero padding.

  A slot is considered valid if:
    - At least one printable ASCII character appears before the terminator.
    - The terminator is CR, LF, or NUL.
    - All bytes after the terminator are 0x00.
    - The label does not exceed 11 characters before the terminator.

  An all-zero slot means no label is set for that partition.

  Slot-to-partition mapping:
    Slot 0  (0x041-0x050)  ->  Partition 1
    Slot 1  (0x051-0x060)  ->  Partition 2
    Slot 2  (0x061-0x070)  ->  Partition 3
    Slot 3  (0x071-0x080)  ->  Partition 4

================================================================================
MBRHDR SIGNATURE REGION (0x1B0-0x1B7)  [MBR88 only]
================================================================================

  Offset  Size   Description
  ------  ----   -----------
  0x1B0   1      Code slack byte.  Always 0x00.  Provides one byte of
                 headroom so boot code growth does not push into 0x1B2.
  0x1B1   1      Cassini byte.  Always 0xD9.  See note 2 in MEMORY MAP.
  0x1B2   5      ASCII signature 'mbr88' (0x6D 0x62 0x72 0x38 0x38).
                 Used to identify the image as an MBR88 boot record.
  0x1B7   1      Version byte.  High nibble = major version,
                 low nibble = minor version.  MBR88 v0.2 = 0x02.

================================================================================
DISK METADATA REGION (0x1B8-0x1BD)
================================================================================

  These fields are part of the traditional MBR specification and are
  present on any MBR-partitioned disk, not only MBR88 images.

  DISK ID (0x1B8-0x1BB)

    A 32-bit little-endian value used by operating systems and disk
    utilities as a unique identifier for the disk.  Introduced by
    Windows NT and used by OS/2 and later systems to track disks across
    reboots and drive letter changes.

    The ID does not need to be cryptographically unique -- just distinct
    enough that two disks on the same machine are unlikely to share a
    value.  A random 32-bit number is fine.

    MBR88 leaves this field as 0x00000000 in the template image.
    mbrpatch will offer to generate an ID automatically when entering
    -n or -u mode if the field is empty.

    Display convention: mbrpatch shows the disk ID as four bytes in
    little-endian order, matching the display used by Linux fdisk and
    similar tools.  Example: a stored value of DE AD BE EF displays as
    EF BE AD DE.  This is confusing exactly once.

  WRITE-PROTECT FLAG (0x1BC-0x1BD)

    A 16-bit hint field introduced alongside the disk ID by Windows NT 3.5.
    The value 0x5A5A indicates the disk should be treated as read-only by
    compliant tools; 0x0000 is normal (no write-protect hint).  DOS 2.0
    through 9x left these bytes as zeros by happenstance -- the field
    simply wasn't defined yet.  Even today it is rarely enforced by
    operating systems or tools.  It is included here because mbrpatch
    exposes it, and knowing it exists beats wondering what those two
    bytes are for.

================================================================================
PARTITION TABLE (0x1BE-0x1FD)
================================================================================

  Four 16-byte partition entries packed end-to-end beginning at 0x1BE.
  Each entry describes one primary partition.  Empty slots are all zeros.

  PARTITION ENTRY FORMAT (16 bytes)

    Offset  Size   Description
    ------  ----   -----------
    0       1      Status byte.
                     0x00 = inactive (not bootable)
                     0x80 = bootable / active
                   Other values are non-standard.
    1       3      CHS address of the first sector (packed; see CHS FORMAT)
    4       1      Partition type byte.  See PARTITION TYPE CODES.
    5       3      CHS address of the last sector (packed; see CHS FORMAT)
    8       4      LBA start sector (32-bit little-endian)
   12       4      LBA sector count (32-bit little-endian)

  mbrpatch computes LBA start and count from the CHS values entered with
  the 'g' and 'n' commands.  XT-class BIOSes use only the CHS fields;
  the LBA fields are for the benefit of modern tools that read the table.

  CHS FORMAT (3 bytes, packed)

    The three-byte CHS field packs cylinder, head, and sector into a
    layout that has caused grown engineers to pause and reach for coffee:

    Byte 0:   Head number (0-255)
    Byte 1:   Bits 7-6 = high two bits of cylinder (bits 9-8)
              Bits 5-0 = sector number (1-63)
    Byte 2:   Low eight bits of cylinder (bits 7-0)

    Cylinder is 10 bits (0-1023), head is 8 bits (0-255), sector is 6
    bits (1-63).  Sector numbers start at 1, not 0.  The IBM XT BIOS
    uses a subset of this range: typically 0-305 cylinders, 0-15 heads,
    1-17 sectors, for a maximum of about 10 MB per disk.

================================================================================
BOOT SIGNATURE (0x1FE-0x1FF)
================================================================================

  0x1FE   0x55
  0x1FF   0xAA

  The two-byte boot signature at the end of the MBR is the oldest
  handshake in the PC ecosystem.  The BIOS checks for 55 AA at this
  offset before treating the sector as bootable.  An MBR without this
  signature is, as far as the BIOS is concerned, not there.  mbrpatch
  refuses to load files that lack it.

================================================================================
PARTITION TYPE CODES
================================================================================

  The partition type byte at offset 4 of each entry is an informal
  registry going back to DOS 2.0.  There is no standards body; values
  were assigned by vendors as needed, which means the history is colorful
  and the list is long.  Common values relevant to XT-class hardware:

  00  Empty (slot unused)
  01  FAT12
  02  Xenix root
  03  Xenix usr
  04  FAT16 <32 MB
  05  Extended (CHS)
  06  FAT16B >=32 MB
  07  HPFS / NTFS / exFAT
  0A  OS/2 Boot Manager
  0B  FAT32
  0C  FAT32 LBA
  0E  FAT16 LBA
  0F  Extended LBA
  11  Hidden FAT12
  14  Hidden FAT16 <32 MB
  16  Hidden FAT16B
  1B  Hidden FAT32
  1C  Hidden FAT32 LBA
  1E  Hidden FAT16 LBA
  64  NetWare 286
  80  ELKS / Old MINIX
  81  MINIX
  82  Linux swap
  83  Linux
  DB  CP/M-86
  EE  GPT protective MBR  (mbrpatch will refuse to write to this disk)
  EF  EFI system partition

  Any value 00-FF is accepted by mbrpatch.  Values not in this list
  display as "Unknown" in the partition summary, but I bet you can 
  find out.  If you know what's on a partition, mbrpatch won't argue.

